Activity-Specific Adjustments: CS 461 Program 2 (Genetic Algorithm Scheduler)
What This Module Does
This module implements the cross-activity fitness rules from Appendix A of the assignment. These are the rules that compare SLA 101 and SLA 191 sections against each other; they can't be scored by looking at one activity in isolation.
The main fitness function only needs to call activity_specific_score(schedule) once per schedule to get the bonus/penalty from these rules.
Where This Fits in the Program
The overall fitness of a schedule is:
total_fitness = sum(per_activity_scores) + activity_specific_score(schedule)

This module handles:
SLA 101 section A vs B time separation
SLA 191 section A vs B time separation
SLA 101 <-> SLA 191 consecutive / same-slot / 1-hour-gap rules
Roman/Beach building-separation penalty for consecutive 101<->191 pairs




How It Works With the Code
The function works with our Gene and Schedule  classes. It looks up the four relevant activities by name ("101 A","101 B", "191 A", "191 B"), so gene order in the schedule doesn't matter.
Expected Gene attributes used:
gene.activity → string like "101 A", "191 B", etc.
gene.time  → string like "10:00 AM", "11:00 AM", "12:00 PM", etc.
gene.room  → string like "Beach 201", "Roman 216", etc.
The function does not use gene.facilitator or gene.fitness since no activity-specific rule depends on who is teaching.
The time strings must match exactly what's in the TIME_TO_HOUR dictionary in the code. Our CSVs use "10:00 AM" format, so that's what the function expects.
Code Walkthrough
Constants:
TIME_TO_HOUR  maps time strings like "10:00 AM" to numeric hours like 10 used for gap math
Helper Functions:
is_roman_or_beach(room_name)returns True if the room is in the Roman or Beach building, used for the building-separation penalty
hour_gap(time_a, time_b)converts two time strings to hours and returns the absolute difference
find_gene(genes, activity_name)searches the gene list for a gene with a matching activity name
Main Function activity_specific_score(schedule):
Finds the four relevant genes by activity name (101 A, 101 B, 191 A, 191 B)
If any of the four are missing, returns 0.0 safely
Checks the SLA 101 section gap  rewards if >4 hours apart, penalizes if same slot
Checks the SLA 191 section gap with same logic
Loops through all four 101<->191 cross-pairs and scores each based on whether they are consecutive, 2 hours apart, or in the same slot
For consecutive pairs, checks if one room is in Roman/Beach and the other is not. If so, applies the building-separation penalty
Returns the total bonus/penalty as a single float

